<HR size="1" color="#a62a2a">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
For any game that has expected upgrades and is designed to last multiple years it is unreasonable to think that all upgrades will be backwards compatible. For any online game it is reasonable to asume that "upgrades" and patches will be necessary feature of continued gameplay.<P>I play on a hopelessly obsolete system (P-pro 200, pre-MMX) that I spent a considerable amount of money upgrading to make it playable. Certain zones (like kunark) can measure the frame rate in seconds rather than frames per second. I recognise that this is the last game I will be able to buy for my present system as I already returned video games LAST year that were incompatable. I accept this because I know that the rest of the world is willing to wait until I and EVERYONE else decide to simultaniously upgrade to the same system.<P>I try to avoid the thought: "I've paid $X.XX per month for the past N months and now I have nothing to show for it." I paid $X.XX for a months enjoyment of using another companys server, electricity, bandwith, and customer support. I now ask myself if I am willing to spend the same amount again for next month.<P>Games come with a minnimum system requirements and a recommended requirements. I don't think any "upgrades" should ever reach the point where the new minnimums excede the original recomended. That demonstrates poor planing on the part of the programers. Not everyone will be able to play all games but not all games are writen to be played by everyone. If they were we'd all be playing solitare and mine sweeper.<P>just my 2 cents
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#a62a2a">
