<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
The first person that responded was on track until they stated that the current system requirements should never exceed the original recommended requirements. What if a game persists 3 or 4 years? How can the system requirements stay constrained to 4 year old technology.<P>I do not know how to quantify what you are asking for Muse. Is $200 per year and a half, two years reasonable?  Sure. I would say that as long as the requirements to play never stretch a user to need absolute cutting edge technology, then upgrades are reasonable. What I mean is, if you took the current requirements and bought a system from scratch, that system should cost somewhere in the medium range of current computer prices. If that is true, than whatever the cost for you to upgrade would seem reasonable to me because you are basically just keeping up with technology, not just with this particular game. If current specs required you to buy a system that would currently be very expensive, say $3000 in today's market, then I would say that is an unreasonable upgrade.<P>There's my two coppers for ya!<P>Rylius
</FONT>
