Hey!  A pentium 200's not that bad, that's what I use, and it runs the game pretty well.  I even manage to keep some of the graphics turned on, at least after this patch - although there are some "anomolies" now.  I think most of the problem comes from parts of your machine like the front-side bus, and memory.  My machine has 128 MB and a 7200 rpm disk with a big paging file, so even though it's only got a 33 mhz controller bus, and a 66 mhz front-side bus, it does alright.<P>But on the original topic, I think that if a game's going to be persistent, from time to time it will require that you upgrade your hardware.  It's impossible to stay competitive otherwise, because all the new games coming out are going to be built with *current* technology in mind, not the stuff we all bought 3 years ago.  It's part of what drives the industry.<P>Seldrin the Unlucky Paladin
</FONT>
