<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
  Ok, let me go at this question from a different perspective.  I work at a software development company and I have to admit that as we put out new versions of our product we often update the requirements such that the end user needs to have a better machine.  As to our product, we also have a client/server architecture just as EQ does.   <BR>  However, there is one key difference with our upgrade path in that we make our new versions of the client/server backwards compatable with the old versions of the client/server.  So, for example, client version 4 can still connect to server version 5.  The way we do this is that we program in such a way that the older client still gets everything it needs, it just doesn't get any of the new features sets as it is unaware of them.  In addition, our version 4 server can communicate with our version 5 server or version 5 client, it's just that certain features our not available.  This would have been one way that Verant could have gone with their EQ client, for instance.  <P>  The downside of this approach is that it requires a much higher commitment, since you must maintain multiple versions of your client - read developer and QE resources are greatly increased - and you must code to maintain both API's in the server backend - read again more dev and QE resources.  Verant has chosen to take the different path of maintaining one code stream and making all their customers go to "version 5" - there are not many products out there that take that approach.  For instance, Microsoft does not make it such that when they release a new Word you have no choice but to upgrade or you cannot read any word docs; Lotus does not make it such that when they release a new version of Notes/Domino you have no choice but to upgrade - in both instances, their customer base (read big business here) would scream their heads off.  <P>  So, my 2 cents is that it truly is not acceptable to expect to be forced to upgrade your hardware to work with an existing version of a product - if Verant had released a version 2 of EQ, then it would be ok for the requirements to change to use ver 2, but to only be patching version 1 and be changing the requirements is, in my opinion, the wrong thing (read if this product were in use by big business, it would not be accepted).  I have yet to see any other product on the market require you to upgrade your hardware because of a patch...<P>Of course, tis only my opinion, my 2cents<P>BTW: Thanks for the maps and info - tis saved my life quite a bit and I really appreciate all the work you've done on em Muse!<P>Justicator<BR>24th Season Wizard<BR>
</FONT>
